{"type":"message","id":"bcc44fdd","parentId":"61721dc3","timestamp":"2026-06-06T13:04:47.457Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I don't see any skills named `tiktok_product_trend` or `ali1688_similar_product` in the skill directories. These are MCP tools from the sorftime-mcp, not standalone skills.\n\nBut wait, the user said \"这两个skill是独立的吗\". Maybe they're referring to skills that were created via skill_workshop? Let me check if there are any skill proposals or installed skills with those names.\n\nActually, the user might be referring to the fact that `tiktok_product_trend` and `ali1688_similar_product` from the sorftime MCP are available as standalone tools (they're listed in the sorftime MCP tools list), and they're asking if these are independent skills. \n\nSo if they're just MCP tools rather than custom skills, the user wants to know if they should be removed. But these are provided by the sorftime-mcp server itself, not created as separate skills, so I should clarify that these aren't separate skills I can delete—they're just part of the sorftime MCP connection.\n\nThe user is asking whether `tiktok_product_trend` and `ali1688_similar_product` work independently, and if so, to delete them. Looking at the sorftime MCP tools, they do function independently—`tiktok_product_trend` queries TikTok product trends while `ali1688_similar_product` finds procurement sources through 1688. The user seems to be asking if these two tools are separate from each other, and if they are, to remove them from the configuration.\n\nBut I think the real issue is that the sorftime MCP is already providing these tools automatically through the MCP server connection, so there's nothing to delete in terms of custom skills—they're just part of the MCP toolset that's already configured. The user's confusion might be about whether they need to do something manually when these tools are already available through the MCP server.\n\nLooking at the workspace skills directory, there's no skill file with those names, so they're definitely coming from the sorftime MCP. Since the user asked if they're independent and should be deleted, and I can see from the tools list that `tiktok_product_trend` supports multiple sites including TH while `ali1688_similar_product` searches by product name, these are functioning properly through the MCP server and don't need any action from me. I should clarify this to the user so they're not worried about unnecessary deletions.\n","thinkingSignature":"bd8ed2575f7bc41d5e891d10c04093d2467f26ee7094a77a74e35c611ce9fc87"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\n`search` 目录没东西，让我看看 workspace 里有没有自定义 skill：\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_1bfe4e233881491ba7935858","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"find /home/halei/workspace-tts -name \"SKILL.md\" -o -name \"*.skill*\" 2>/dev/null | head -20\n# 也看看 mcporter 有没有额外的 mcp 配置\ncat /home/halei/workspace-tts/config/mcporter.json"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":2236,"output":585,"cacheRead":125615,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":128436,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1780751074067,"responseId":"06734de282236cab05d9283932118076"}}
